<br>
I think I see what you are saying, now. I think we agree that motion is involved in our sense of time. &quot;Perfection&quot; has always been problematic for me, though. We can logically analyze and empirically analyze items in the world, but how would we judge something as being the &quot;most perfect&quot;. It would be like grading the quality of diamonds. We can only compare those items within the realm of our experiences. Anything outside experience (not in strictly an empirical sense of the word) can't possibly be used in our analysis of perfections. In short, we don't know what the scale could possibly look like, so our talk of perfections become vacuous. I believe the philosopher David Hume covers this very well in his  &quot;Enquiry conerning the Principle of Human Understanding&quot; and in his &quot;Treatise of Human Nature&quot;. Immanuel Kant also covers ideas over &quot;perfections&quot; in his &quot;Critique of Pure Reason&quot;.<br>
<br>
Thank you for sharing the last half of your post. I like your sense of humor. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
